responses: You can reduce calories by choosing low-calorie, high-volume foods such as vegetables, salads, lean meats, eggs, and Greek yogurt. Drinking water before meals helps as well.

A simple way to reduce calories is to replace high-calorie foods with lighter alternatives, eat slower, and avoid late-night snacking.
Increasing protein and fiber helps you feel full and naturally reduces calorie intake without feeling deprived.

If you prefer something light, fruit, rice cakes, a protein shake, or low-fat yogurt can fuel your workout without feeling heavy.
Avoid heavy meals before training. Choose foods that digest easily, such as fruit, oats, yogurt, or a small lean protein portion with carbs.

responses: Good post-workout stretches include hamstring stretches, quad stretches, glute stretches, chest stretches, back stretches, and shoulder stretches. Hold each stretch for 20–30 seconds.
A simple post-workout routine can include hamstring stretch, quad stretch, hip flexor stretch, calf stretch, chest opener, shoulder stretch, and a gentle spinal twist.
Stretching after training helps reduce stiffness. Focus on major muscle groups: legs, hips, chest, shoulders, and back. Hold each stretch without bouncing.
To reduce soreness, stretch your legs, hips, back, and shoulders after training. Combine slow stretching with controlled breathing for better relaxation.
A balanced cool-down includes light walking for a couple of minutes followed by static stretching for all the muscles you trained that day.
